<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="1" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1425,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1686,1711]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="21" reason="1">Description.</emphasis>
Size: apterous form: males, length 7.50–8.00, width 2.31–2.47 (
<typeStatus box="[1085,1188,1686,1710]" pageId="1" pageNumber="21">holotype</typeStatus>
: 8.00, 2.44), females, length 8.35–8.75, width 2.81–2.94 (
<typeStatus box="[555,651,1724,1748]" pageId="1" pageNumber="21">allotype</typeStatus>
: 8.60, 2.79); macropterous males: length 7.80–8.20, width 2.34–2.44, macropterous female: length 9.20, width 2.95.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1425,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="21">
Color (
<figureCitation box="[282,394,1798,1822]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1909,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-35@2.[151,1436,195,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. 1–2. Holotype, male: 1. Habitus, 2. Abdominal venter. 3. Dorsum of female (allotype)." pageId="1" pageNumber="21">Figs. 1–3</figureCitation>
): Apterous form: dorsum mainly dark brown to black; antennae black; head with yellow marking on posterior margin; rostrum mainly dark brown; pronotum with median dark yellow stripe about same length as pronotum; pronotum, pronotal lobe, and metanotum with scattered golden pubescence; front legs mainly black with basal and apical part of femur yellowish brown; middle and hind legs yellow to brown; ventral, lateral sides and abdominal terga yellowish brown, with dense silvery pubescence. Macropterous form: similar to apterous form, wing chiefly brown, wing veins with golden pubescence.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="2" pageNumber="22" startId="2.[151,263,1909,1932]" targetBox="[151,1436,195,1885]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1909,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,318,1909,1932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">FIGURES 1–3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[328,545,1909,1931]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[328,394,1909,1931]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">Gerris</emphasis>
(s.str.) 
<emphasis box="[478,545,1910,1931]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="22">curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[556,615,1910,1931]" pageId="2" pageNumber="22" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
1–2. Holotype, male: 1. Habitus, 2. Abdominal venter. 3. Dorsum of female (allotype).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,512,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">Structural characteristics:</emphasis>
Apterous male (
<typeStatus box="[706,811,151,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">holotype</typeStatus>
): Head width 1.46, interocular width 0.89, eye length 0.71. Lengths of antennal segments 1–4: 1.25: 0.76: 0.73: 1.11. Pronotum length 2.89. Mesosternum length 2.64, metasternum length 0.60. Lengths of leg segments (femur: tibia: tarsus 1: tarsus 2): front leg: 2.25: 1.89: 0.24: 0.32; middle leg: 5.40: 4.36: 2.71: 0.60; hind leg: 5.20: 2.67: 1.08: 0.45. Front femur moderately incrassate, length about 5.2 times of width (width 0.43), front tibia slightly curved. Combined length of abdominal sterna 2–7: 2.18; sternum 7 medially notched (length 0.62) (
<figureCitation box="[645,728,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1909,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-35@2.[151,1436,195,1885]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. 1–2. Holotype, male: 1. Habitus, 2. Abdominal venter. 3. Dorsum of female (allotype)." pageId="3" pageNumber="23">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[742,758,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[174,1425,512,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-200@3.[151,1436,481,1950]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4–8. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. (4–7: holotype, male) 4. front leg, 5. abdominal venter, 6. connexival angles on lateral view, 7. connexival angles on dorsal view; 8. connexival spines of macropterous male on lateral view." pageId="3" pageNumber="23">5</figureCitation>
). Ventral length of abdominal segment 8: 0.49. Sterna 2–5 slightly impressed medially; sterna 6 and 7 with distinct median impression; connexival angles short; sub-lateral impressions on ventral side of abdominal segment 8 usually covered with silvery pubescence (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1305,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[174,1425,512,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-200@3.[151,1436,481,1950]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4–8. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. (4–7: holotype, male) 4. front leg, 5. abdominal venter, 6. connexival angles on lateral view, 7. connexival angles on dorsal view; 8. connexival spines of macropterous male on lateral view." pageId="3" pageNumber="23">Figs. 6, 7</figureCitation>
). Genitalia: pygophore simple, proctiger pointed; vesical sclerites of endosoma as in 
<figureCitation box="[966,1086,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1841,1864]" captionTargetBox="[192,1415,253,1764]" captionTargetId="figure-70@4.[151,1436,229,1803]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. 9–11: vesical sclerites of male endosoma (dorsal plate omitted), 9. dorsal view, 10. lateral view, 11. ventral view (ds—dorsal sclerite, ls—lateral sclerite, als—apical sclerite, vs—ventral sclerite). 12–14: abdomen of female (allotype), 12. ventral view, 13. connexival spines on lateral view, 14. connexival spines on dorsal view." pageId="3" pageNumber="23">Figs. 9–11</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="3" pageNumber="23" startId="3.[151,264,1936,1959]" targetBox="[174,1425,512,1902]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1936,1989]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,316,1936,1959]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">FIGURES 4–8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[324,537,1936,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[324,390,1936,1958]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">Gerris</emphasis>
(s.str.) 
<emphasis box="[470,537,1937,1958]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="23">curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[546,602,1937,1958]" pageId="3" pageNumber="23" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(4–7: holotype, male) 4. front leg, 5. abdominal venter, 6. connexival angles on lateral view, 7. connexival angles on dorsal view; 8. connexival spines of macropterous male on lateral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption pageId="4" pageNumber="24" startId="4.[151,264,1841,1864]" targetBox="[192,1415,253,1764]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1841,1930]" pageId="4" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,326,1841,1864]" pageId="4" pageNumber="24">FIGURES 9–14.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[332,541,1842,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[332,398,1842,1864]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="24">Gerris</emphasis>
(s.str.) 
<emphasis box="[473,541,1843,1864]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="24">curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[546,600,1843,1864]" pageId="4" pageNumber="24" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
9–11: vesical sclerites of male endosoma (dorsal plate omitted), 9. dorsal view, 10. lateral view, 11. ventral view (ds—dorsal sclerite, ls—lateral sclerite, als—apical sclerite, vs—ventral sclerite). 12–14: abdomen of female (allotype), 12. ventral view, 13. connexival spines on lateral view, 14. connexival spines on dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1091]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">
Apterous female (
<typeStatus box="[407,504,151,175]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">allotype</typeStatus>
): Head width 1.51, interocular width 0.92, eye length 0.68. Lengths of antennal segments 1–4: 1.32: 0.82: 0.73: 1.14. Pronotum length 3.10. Mesosternum length 2.71, metasternum length 0.67. Lengths of leg segments (femur: tibia: tarsus 1: tarsus 2): front leg: 2.33: 1.88: 0.24: 0.33; middle leg: 5.30: 4.41: 2.64: 0.68; hind leg: 5.20: 2.81: 1.05: 0.48. Front femur moderately incrassate, length about 5.68 times of width (width 0.41), front tibia slightly curved. Combined length of abdominal sterna 2–7: 2.84; sternum 7 length 0.64, posterior margin slightly concave. Connexival spines well produced, reaching apex of proctiger, pointed dorsocaudad (on lateral view) and curved inwards (on dorsal view), thus usually not visible on ventral view (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1841,1864]" captionTargetBox="[192,1415,253,1764]" captionTargetId="figure-70@4.[151,1436,229,1803]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. 9–11: vesical sclerites of male endosoma (dorsal plate omitted), 9. dorsal view, 10. lateral view, 11. ventral view (ds—dorsal sclerite, ls—lateral sclerite, als—apical sclerite, vs—ventral sclerite). 12–14: abdomen of female (allotype), 12. ventral view, 13. connexival spines on lateral view, 14. connexival spines on dorsal view." pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Figs. 12–14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1091]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">
Macropterous male: similar to apterous form, but connexival spines distinct and longer that in apterous form (
<figureCitation box="[159,228,468,492]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[174,1425,512,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-200@3.[151,1436,481,1950]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4–8. Gerris (s.str.) curvus sp. n. (4–7: holotype, male) 4. front leg, 5. abdominal venter, 6. connexival angles on lateral view, 7. connexival angles on dorsal view; 8. connexival spines of macropterous male on lateral view." pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Structural measurements as follows: Head width 1.43, interocular width 0.87, eye length 0.67. Lengths of antennal segments 1–4: 1.35: 0.73: 0.73: 1.03. Pronotum length 3.04. Mesosternum length 2.64, metasternum length 0.63. Lengths of leg segments (femur: tibia: tarsus 1: tarsus 2): front leg: 2.30: 1.96: 0.25: 0.35; middle leg: 5.40: 4.26: 2.54: 0.71; hind leg: 5.20: 2.64: 0.86: 0.51. Front femur length about 6.0 times of width (width 0.38). Combined length of abdominal sterna 2–7: 2.40; sternum 7 length 0.63. Ventral length of abdominal segment 8: 0.44. Wings not reaching tip of proctiger, wing length ca. 4.80.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1091]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,432,679,704]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" reason="1">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
According to Andersen (1993), 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant, 1910" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[798,1240,680,704]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[798,871,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris</emphasis>
(s. str.) 
<emphasis box="[963,1081,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">nepalensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Distant, W. L." box="[1089,1240,680,704]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" pagination="140 - 153" refId="ref6266" refString="Distant, W. L. (1910) Some undescribed Gerrinae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, ser. 8, v. 5, 140 - 153." type="journal article" year="1910">Distant, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
stands alone as a single-species group, which is defined by the following characteristics: long and slender antennae and legs; middle of head shiny; abdominal tergum distinctly shiny; vesical sclerites simple; well-produced connexival processes. 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,305,785,809]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[151,305,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[311,370,786,809]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[598,795,785,809]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[598,795,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it fits well in the diagnosis of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[1201,1348,785,809]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[1201,1348,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<emphasis box="[234,296,821,844]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">sensu</emphasis>
Andersen, 1993) but it differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[712,862,821,845]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[712,862,821,845]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several characteristics. In males, the abdominal venter of 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[262,418,856,880]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[262,418,856,880]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[428,489,856,879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is medially impressed, especially in sterna 6–7, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[1149,1299,856,880]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[1149,1299,856,880]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there is no median impression. The endosoma structures are similar, but the lateral sclerites of 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[1102,1257,891,915]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1102,1257,891,915]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1266,1327,891,914]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are more slender, and their posterior part not as broadened as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[764,913,926,950]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[764,913,926,950]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In females, tergite 7 of 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[1188,1343,926,950]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1188,1343,926,950]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1350,1410,927,950]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is distinctly narrower in the posterior part while in that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[773,922,961,985]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[773,922,961,985]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior width is subequal to the anterior width. The connexival spines in females are also distinctly different in two species: straight, parallel and rather pointed caudad in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1910" box="[368,520,1032,1056]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis box="[368,520,1032,1056]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">G. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; pointed dorsocaudad (in lateral view) and curved inwards (in dorsal view) in 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus, 2012" authorityName="Polhemus" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,305,1067,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Gerris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[151,305,1067,1091]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="25">Gerris curvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[313,372,1067,1090]" pageId="5" pageNumber="25" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
